                {
                  q: 'What is the difference between None and NaN in Pandas, and when does each appear?',
                  a: 'None is Python\'s null object — appears in object-dtype columns (strings, mixed types). NaN is IEEE 754 "not a number" — appears in float64 columns. Pandas uses NaN for numeric missing because None cannot be stored in a NumPy float array. When you assign None to a float column, Pandas silently converts it to NaN. pd.isna() detects both, making it the universal safe check. Pandas 1.0+ introduces pd.NA for nullable integer and boolean extensions.',
